0.body: Ayaka project is a project for OSPP 2022. It is a voice novel engine which aims at 3 goals: simple, free, concentrate.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: A voice novel should be easy to author. The author need little knowledge of programming. We provide a config file format based on YAML and TeX-like commands. It is easy to learn and author your own voice novel.
1.title: Simple

11.breadcrumbs: Quick start » Release build of frontends
11.title: Release build of frontends

12.body:
$ # Run Fibonacci2
$ make example-Fibonacci2

12.title: Run examples

13.body: Our config file is based on YAML. The structure is simple to author. The articles below uses ayaka-check to show the example, it may behave a little different in GUI. To run the example, you need to create a config file with full structure , go to the bins folder and run $ cargo run --package ayaka-check -- path/to/config.yaml --auto
13.title: Config

15.body: The total config file is a Game object. Here shows the properties: Property Description title The title of the game. base_lang The base language. paras The Paragraph objects, indexed by locale. author Optional. The author of the game. plugins Optional. The PluginConfig object. res Optional. The resources, indexed by locale. props Optional. The custom properties. The PluginConfig object contains the base directory and the plugin names: Property Description dir The directory. modules The plugin names. A Paragraph object is a collection of texts: Property Description tag The tag and key of the paragraph. texts The texts. title Optional. The title of the paragraph. next Optional. The next paragraph.
15.title: Properties

16.body:
This is a config example, with 2 paragraphs. title: Title
base_lang: en
paras: en: - tag: para1 texts: - This is the first line. - This is the second line. next: para2 - tag: para2 texts: - The first line of the second paragraph. The output will be This is the first line.
This is the second line.
The first line of the second paragraph. You can see that the game starts at the first paragraph para1, and it jumps to para2 after para1 ends. The game exits after para2 ends, because it doesn't specify the next paragraph.
16.title: Basic example

17.body: The dialogues should be marked with the speaking character. We specify a character with \ch{}{} command.
17.title: Specify character

18.body:
The character names should be placed in res at the front of the game. Not only because the character name is too long to type again and again, but also to make i18n easy. The key of the character name should be prefixed with ch_: res: en: ch_foo: A. Foo ch_bar: B. Bar You can then specify the character with the command: - \ch{foo}This is the first line.
- \ch{bar}This is the second line. These two lines will output as: _A. Foo_This is the first line.
_B. Bar_This is the second line.
18.breadcrumbs: Config » Specify character » Add the character names
18.title: Add the character names

19.body:
Sometimes we need a temporary alias of the current character: - \ch{foo}{Person 1st}This is the first line.
- \ch{bar}{Person 2nd}This is the second line. The output will be _Person 1st_This is the first line.
_Person 2nd_This is the second line.
19.breadcrumbs: Config » Specify character » Specify the alias of the character
19.title: Specify the alias of the character

2.body: You are free to implement anything you'd like with our script and plugin system. The script is simple, but also strong with the plugin system. The plugin system provides possibility to calculate and hook important parts in the runtime.
2.title: Free

20.body:
We provide an easier grammar to specify the character: - /foo//This is the first line.
- /bar/Person 2nd/This is the second line. Note the double slashes in /foo// could not be simplified.
20.title: Simple grammar

21.body: The \ch{}{} command could be called many times, but only the last one affects.
21.title: Warning

22.body:
The resources are indexed by locale: res: en: foo: Foo value bar: Bar value You can specify other locales, too. The keys not specified in other locales will fallback to base_lang ones. base_lang: en
res: en: foo: Foo bar: Bar zh: foo: 天 bar: 地
22.title: Resources

23.body:
You can reference resources in texts with \res{} command. - 'The foo value: \res{foo}'
- 'The bar value: \res{bar}'
23.title: Reference resources

25.body: The i18n feature are supported by ICU4X with CLDR data. We use CLDR to choose the best fit locale for current system.
25.title: ICU

26.title: Simplify translation

27.body: The resources, commands, and even paragraphs could be fell back, if a translated one is not apparent. However, some other ones couldn't be fell back.
27.title: Fallback

28.body: The \res and \exec commands couldn't be fell back. If there's no corresponding commands in the translated lines, they won't be referenced or executed. However, the \ch and \switch commands could be fell back.
28.title: The \res and \exec commands

29.body: However, if a certain translated line is empty, it will fall back to the base language one.
29.breadcrumbs: Config » Internationalization » Fallback with empty text
29.title: Fallback with empty text

3.body: The project is separated into 4 parts: runtime, plugins, config, frontend. You can concentrate at one part without knowing about others. If you like, you can write config file only, and author a voice novel. You can also write your own fantastic game by customizing the frontend.
3.title: Concentrate

30.body: The switches could be specified with \switch{}{}{} command. The \switch command in one line of text are in the same series. The first parameter is the display text; the second parameter is the action script; the third parameter is a boolean expression of whether the switch is enabled. For the second and the third parameter, see Script . - | Choose a switch: \switch{Switch 1}{$s = 1} \switch{Switch 2}{$s = 2} \switch{Not enabled}{}{false}
30.title: Switches

31.body:
The script we use is dynamic typed. The only supported types are unit ~, boolean, integer, and string. pub enum RawValue { Unit, Bool(bool), Num(i64), Str(String),
}
31.title: Script

32.body: Execute a piece of script(we call it program ) with \exec{} command: - 1 + 1 = \exec{1 + 1} The output is 1 + 1 = 2 The script 1 + 1 is evaluated, and the result is 2. It is then converted to string and appended to the text.
32.title: Execute scripts

33.body:
With the config file, we can even calculate some math problems. For example, Fibonacci: - tag: init texts: - 1 - \exec{$n = 50; $a = 1; $b = 1; $i = 1; $b} next: loop
- tag: loop texts: - \exec{c = $b; $b += $a; $a = c; $i += 1; $b} next: \exec{if($i < $n, "loop")}
33.title: Example: Fibonacci

34.body: The runtime, aka "backend", is the engine of a game. It provides functionality to load config, settings, plugins, and control the full status.

38.body: All plugins should target WebAssembly. We now support wasm32-unknown-unknown and wasm32-wasi targets. The plugin runtime is supported by Wasmer . Our platform support is largely limited by this engine. We provide a crate ayaka-bindings to easily author a plugin in Rust.
38.title: Plugin

39.body: Specify the plugin directory in the config file: plugins: dir: path/to/plugins The runtime will try to load all WebAssembly file in the directory. If you want to specify some of them, or specify the load order, specify them in modules: plugins: dir: path/to/plugins modules: - foo - bar You don't need to specify the extension.
39.title: Load plugins

40.body: All plugins are script plugins. Scripts could call methods in the script plugins.
40.title: Script plugin

41.body: A plugin method is referenced with <module>.<fn>(...) grammar. If you would like to call the rnd function in random module, - \exec{random.rnd()} Pass the parameters in the brace (). As the scripts are calculated at runtime, if there's no plugin called random, or no method called rnd inside random, it will give a warning, and continue with RawValue::Unit.
41.title: Calling methods

42.breadcrumbs: Plugin » Script plugin » Author a script plugin
42.title: Author a script plugin

43.body: There are some existing script (only) plugins: Plugin Description format Format strings. ayalog Log to runtime. random Generate random numbers.

6.body: Windows 10+ is recommended but any Windows that Rust supports is OK. WebView2 is required by Tauri . It comes with the latest Edge browser. To run the Makefile toolchain, you need GNU Make from MSYS2 project, either for Msys2(make) or Mingw64(mingw32-make). Note that if you have a WSL bash.exe in PATH before MSYS2 one, the npm command may fail.
6.title: Windows

7.body: webkit2gtk is needed. We only support webkit2gtk-4.0 required by Tauri .
7.title: Linux

8.body: Generally we don't need anything more, but you should ensure there a make.
